-- HTN test
update public.articles
set content = '{"schemaVersion": 2, "sections": [{"key": "definition", "body": "Hypertension is defined as a sustained elevation of arterial blood pressure, specifically systolic blood pressure (SBP) ≥140 mmHg and/or diastolic blood pressure (DBP) ≥90 mmHg, measured on at least two separate occasions after initial resting, distinguishing it from transient blood pressure fluctuations."}, {"key": "epidemiology", "body": "Globally, an estimated 1.28 billion adults aged 30-79 years have hypertension. \n- Prevalence: 20-30% in the adult population in Ethiopia and Sub-Saharan Africa.\n- High-Risk Groups: Predominantly affects middle-aged and elderly individuals, but increasingly seen in younger adults due to lifestyle changes.\n- Regional Pattern: Higher rates in urban areas.\n- Seasonal Pattern: No significant seasonal pattern for primary hypertension."}, {"key": "etiology", "body": "PRIMARY (ESSENTIAL):\n- Accounts for 90-95% of cases, influenced by genetics, high salt diet, obesity, and sedentary lifestyle.\nSECONDARY:\n- Renal: Renal parenchymal disease (e.g., chronic glomerulonephritis, diabetic nephropathy), Renovascular disease (e.g., renal artery stenosis).\n- Endocrine: Conn''s syndrome, Cushing''s syndrome, Pheochromocytoma, thyroid dysfunction.\n- Structural: Coarctation of the aorta, Obstructive Sleep Apnea.\n- Drug-induced: NSAIDs, oral contraceptives."}, {"key": "pathophysiology", "body": "Hypertension often begins with a combination of genetic predisposition and environmental factors like high sodium intake and obesity, leading to endothelial dysfunction and activation of the Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone System (RAAS). This results in increased peripheral vascular resistance and/or increased cardiac output, causing a sustained elevation in arterial blood pressure. Over time, this chronic high pressure damages the walls of blood vessels and leads to hypertrophy of the left ventricle, explaining why patients develop symptoms like headaches (due to cerebral microvascular changes) or visual disturbances (due to retinal vessel damage) as end-organ damage progresses."}, {"key": "clinicalFeatures", "body": "SYMPTOMS:\n- Headache (often occipital, worse in the morning)\n- Palpitations\n- Fatigue\n- Dizziness\n- Epistaxis\nSIGNS:\n- Elevated blood pressure readings\n- S4 gallop on cardiac auscultation\n- Retinal changes on fundoscopy\n- Ankle edema (often indicates heart failure or kidney disease)\nEARLY FEATURES:\n- Often asymptomatic (the ''silent killer'')\nLATE FEATURES (END-ORGAN DAMAGE):\n- Blurred vision (retinopathy)\n- Chest pain (ischemia)\n- Shortness of breath (heart failure)\n- Neurological deficits (stroke)\nOFTEN MISSED:\n- Ankle edema as an indicator of secondary systemic failure."}, {"key": "redFlags", "body": "\n- SBP >180 mmHg or DBP >120 mmHg with new acute end-organ damage\n- Sudden severe headache with focal neurological deficit\n- Acute chest pain with SBP >160 mmHg\n- Acute visual loss with severe hypertension\n- Rapidly worsening shortness of breath with SBP >180 mmHg\n- New onset focal neurological deficit"}, {"key": "approach", "body": "1. Immediate ABC and stabilisation: If hypertensive emergency, ensure patent airway, adequate breathing, and circulation. Establish IV access and continuous vital sign monitoring. 2. Focused 2-minute history: Ask ''Do you have headache, chest pain, vision changes, or weakness?'' ''Any history of kidney disease, diabetes, or previous stroke?'' ''What medications are you currently taking?'' 3. Targeted exam: Measure BP in both arms, perform fundoscopy, auscultate heart for murmurs/gallops, check for peripheral edema and neurological deficits. 4. Investigations in strict priority order: Urinalysis (for proteinuria/hematuria), Serum Creatinine and Electrolytes, Fasting Blood Glucose, ECG, Fundoscopy. 5. Start treatment: If not an emergency, initiate oral therapy, e.g., Hydrochlorothiazide 25mg PO daily. If emergency, IV Labetalol 20mg IV bolus over 2 minutes. 6. Reassess and escalate criteria: Recheck BP in 1 hour (if emergency) or 1 week (if stable). Escalate therapy if target BP not met or new symptoms develop."}, {"key": "diagnosis", "body": "CLINICAL:\n- SBP ≥140 mmHg and/or DBP ≥90 mmHg on at least two separate occasions, 4-6 hours apart, after 5 minutes of rest.\nBLOOD TESTS / LABS:\n- Serum Creatinine >1.2 mg/dL (suggests renal impairment) - Available (referral only).\n- Urinalysis: Proteinuria (suggests renal damage) - Available (primary).\n- Fasting Blood Glucose.\nIMAGING / DIAGNOSTICS:\n- ECG: Left Ventricular Hypertrophy (Sokolow-Lyon index >35mm) - Available (district).\n- Fundoscopy: Grade III/IV retinopathy (hemorrhages, exudates, papilledema) - Available (district).\n- Renal ultrasound: Small kidneys or renal artery stenosis - Available (referral only).\nGOLD STANDARD:\n- Ambulatory Blood Pressure Monitoring (ABPM) - Not available in Ethiopia."}, {"key": "treatment", "body": "MILD-OUTPATIENT:\n- Ethiopian MoH first-line: Hydrochlorothiazide 25mg PO daily.\n- Duration: Lifelong.\nMODERATE-WARD:\n- Step-up to combination therapy, e.g., add Amlodipine 5mg PO daily.\n- Monitor: Blood pressure, electrolytes (K+), and renal function.\nSEVERE-ICU (HYPERTENSIVE EMERGENCY):\n- IV Labetalol 20mg IV bolus over 2 minutes, then 20-80mg IV every 10-15 minutes or continuous infusion.\n- Goal: Reduce MAP by 10-20% in the first hour, then by 25% over 24 hours."}, {"key": "contraindications", "body": "NEVER give ACE inhibitors (e.g., Enalapril) in bilateral renal artery stenosis because it can precipitate acute kidney injury. CAUTION with Beta-blockers (e.g., Atenolol) in severe asthma or COPD. NEVER give Hydrochlorothiazide in severe hyponatremia (<125 mmol/L). CAUTION with Calcium Channel Blockers in patients with significant peripheral edema."}, {"key": "dontMiss", "body": "Pheochromocytoma | Trio of headache, palpitations, sweating reveals it.\nRenal Artery Stenosis | Abdominal bruit or AKI after starting ACE inhibitor reveals it.\nPre-eclampsia/Eclampsia | New onset HTN + proteinuria + edema after 20 weeks reveals it.\nThyrotoxicosis | Weight loss + goiter + tachycardia reveals it."}, {"key": "complications", "body": "EARLY (0-48h):\n- Hypertensive encephalopathy (cerebral edema)\n- Acute pulmonary edema (acute LV failure)\nSUBACUTE (DAYS-WEEKS):\n- Acute kidney injury (due to severe vasoconstriction)\n- Stroke (ischemic or hemorrhagic)\nLATE (WEEKS-MONTHS):\n- Chronic kidney disease (hypertensive nephrosclerosis - commonly missed)\n- Heart failure (LVH and dysfunction)\n- Coronary artery disease\n- Retinopathy (permanent vision loss)"}, {"key": "clinicalPearls", "body": "Pearl 1: Always measure blood pressure in both arms; a difference of >20 mmHg suggests subclavian stenosis or aortic dissection. Pearl 2: Never rely on symptoms to gauge severity; a patient with SBP 200 mmHg can feel fine but remains at high risk for stroke. Pearl 3: Regular palpation of the radial pulse can reveal cardiac complications like atrial fibrillation in low-resource settings. Pearl 4: Never discharge a patient with uncontrolled severe hypertension without a follow-up plan; the first stroke is often the only window for intervention."}, {"key": "ethiopianContext", "body": "\n- Burden: Estimated prevalence is 20-30% in adults; higher in urban centers like Addis Ababa.\n- MoH first-line: Hydrochlorothiazide (often combined with Enalapril or Amlodipine).\n- Local Co-morbidities: HIV (which can worsen existing HTN or cause secondary HTN), diabetes, and CKD.\n- District Workaround: Training community health workers for routine BP screening and referral of high-risk individuals."}, {"key": "mnemonics", "body": "ABCD FOR ANTIHYPERTENSIVES:\n- A = ACE inhibitors/ARBs: Block the RAAS.\n- B = Beta-blockers: Reduce heart rate and contractility.\n- C = Calcium channel blockers: Cause vasodilation.\n- D = Diuretics: Reduce fluid volume.\nCHART FOR SECONDARY CAUSES:\n- C = Cushing''s syndrome\n- H = Hyperaldosteronism\n- A = Aortic coarctation\n- R = Renal artery stenosis\n- T = Thyroid disease / Pheochromocytoma"}, {"key": "examTraps", "body": "TRAP: Assuming a single high BP reading means hypertension. | REALITY: Diagnosis requires sustained elevation on multiple readings taken after rest.\nTRAP: Thinking headache is always a reliable symptom. | REALITY: Most hypertensive patients are asymptomatic; severe headache is a sign of emergency, not routine HTN.\nTRAP: Prescribing ACE inhibitors to a patient with bilateral renal artery stenosis. | REALITY: This can cause acute renal failure by reducing glomerular perfusion.\nTRAP: Ignoring a >20 mmHg difference between arms. | REALITY: This can indicate serious underlying vascular disease."}]}'::jsonb
where id = '810358cd-5b6c-4908-b0c0-b8a2d3058863';

